  "summary": "This is a large-scale VPC restructuring that modifies 5 resources simultaneously, affecting 12 downstream services across 2 AWS accounts and 2 regions.\n\n**Highest Risk: Cross-Account RDS Cluster (Score: 88/100, Critical)**\nThe Aurora cluster in account 987654321098 (eu-west-1) uses VPC peering to connect to the primary VPC being modified. The CIDR block change will invalidate the peering route tables, severing the cross-account database replication. Suggested mitigation: Update VPC peering routes in both accounts simultaneously, or temporarily pause replication during the change window.\n\n**Critical Risk: Production ECS Services (Score: 82/100, Critical)**\nTwo ECS Fargate services (api-service, worker-service) run in the subnets being modified. Subnet CIDR changes require the tasks to be redeployed with new IP addresses, causing brief downtime. The NAT gateway replacement will also interrupt outbound internet access for these services during the transition. Suggested mitigation: Deploy replacement subnets first, migrate ECS tasks, then decommission old subnets.\n\n**High Risk: Lambda Functions (Score: 68/100, High)**\nFour Lambda functions are configured with VPC access using the affected subnets. They will lose network connectivity during the subnet modification and NAT gateway replacement. Cold starts after the change will take longer as ENIs are re-provisioned. Suggested mitigation: Temporarily remove VPC configuration from non-critical Lambda functions, or accept brief invocation failures during the maintenance window.\n\nOverall, this change requires careful orchestration. We recommend a maintenance window with the following order: (1) create new subnets, (2) migrate workloads, (3) update peering routes, (4) replace NAT gateway, (5) decommission old subnets. Estimated safe execution time: 45-60 minutes.",
